  "prompt": "What is the difference between together and with?",
  "response": "While both \"together\" and \"with\" indicate some form of association or connection, they emphasize different aspects of that connection. Here's a breakdown of the key differences:\n\n**Together:**\n\n*   **Emphasizes unity and shared action or presence.** It suggests that people or things are acting, being, or located in close proximity and often as a single unit or group.\n*   **Implies joint effort or common activity.** It often signifies collaboration, cooperation, or being in the same place at the same time.\n*   **Can be used to denote a romantic or intimate relationship.**\n*   **Often functions as an adverb** describing *how* something is done.\n\n    *   **Examples:**\n        *   \"We worked **together** to solve the problem.\" (emphasizes collaboration)\n        *   \"They sang **together** in harmony.\" (shared activity)\n        *   \"We went to the park **together**.\" (shared presence)\n        *   \"They are **together**.\" (romantic relationship)\n\n**With:**\n\n*   **Indicates accompaniment, possession, or a tool/instrument.** It shows that something is included, possessed, or used in relation to something else.\n*   **Is more general and doesn't necessarily imply shared action.**  It simply shows a connection or association.\n*   **Functions as a preposition** to link a noun or pronoun to another part of the sentence.\n\n    *   **Examples:**\n        *   \"I went to the store **with** my friend.\" (accompaniment)\n        *   \"He has a house **with** a garden.\" (possession/inclusion)\n        *   \"She opened the can **with** a knife.\" (tool)\n        *   \"The soup is made **with** tomatoes.\" (ingredient)\n\n**Here's a table summarizing the differences:**\n\n| Feature        | Together                                   | With                                        |\n|----------------|--------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|\n| **Emphasis**     | Unity, shared action/presence, collaboration | Accompaniment, inclusion, possession, tool |\n| **Implication**  | Joint effort, common activity              | Connection, association                    |\n| **Part of Speech** | Adverb (primarily)                        | Preposition                                 |\n\n**Examples to further illustrate the difference:**\n\n*   \"We ate dinner **together**.\" (Implies a shared meal and perhaps conversation)\n*   \"I ate dinner **with** my family.\" (Simply indicates who you were eating with, not necessarily that you were all sharing food or actively interacting.)\n\n*   \"The dancers moved **together** in perfect synchrony.\" (Emphasizes the coordinated movement)\n*   \"The dancers moved **with** grace.\" (Describes the quality of their movement, not their association)\n\n**In short:**\n\nUse \"together\" when you want to highlight unity, cooperation, or a shared experience. Use \"with\" when you want to indicate accompaniment, possession, inclusion, or the use of something in relation to something else.\n",
